    <%# SEO Article Content %>
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Amortization Schedule Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Enter your loan amount, annual interest rate, and loan term in years to generate a complete amortization schedule. The calculator instantly computes your fixed monthly payment and creates a detailed month-by-month table showing exactly how each payment is split between principal reduction and interest charges. You can scroll through the full schedule to see your balance decrease over time.
      </p>
      <p>
        This tool is invaluable for understanding the true cost of a mortgage, auto loan, or personal loan. By examining the schedule, you can see that early payments are heavily weighted toward interest, while later payments primarily reduce the principal. This knowledge helps you make informed decisions about extra payments and refinancing.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Understanding Loan Amortization</h2>
      <p>
        Loan amortization is the process of spreading out a loan into a series of fixed payments over time. The standard amortization formula ensures that each monthly payment covers the interest accrued that month plus a portion of the outstanding principal. Because interest is calculated on the remaining balance, the interest-to-principal ratio shifts dramatically over the life of the loan. In a typical 30-year mortgage, more than 60% of the first year's payments go to interest, but in the final year, nearly 100% goes to principal.
      </p>

      <h3>Benefits of Viewing the Full Schedule</h3>
      <p>
        Seeing the full amortization table reveals patterns that summary numbers cannot show. You can identify exactly when your principal payments exceed your interest payments (the tipping point), calculate how much interest you save by making an extra payment at any specific point, and compare the total interest cost of different loan terms. For example, switching from a 30-year to a 15-year mortgage roughly doubles the monthly payment but typically saves more than half the total interest.
      </p>

      <h3>Strategies for Accelerating Payoff</h3>
      <p>
        Extra payments applied directly to principal can dramatically shorten your loan term. Adding even $100 per month to a $250,000 mortgage at 6.5% saves over $50,000 in interest and pays off the loan more than 5 years early. Biweekly payment plans, where you pay half the monthly amount every two weeks, result in 26 half-payments (13 full payments) per year instead of 12, effectively adding one extra payment annually. Always confirm with your lender that extra payments are applied to principal and that there are no prepayment penalties.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What is an amortization schedule?</h3>
      <p>
        An amortization schedule is a complete table showing every monthly payment over the life of a loan, broken down into the principal portion, interest portion, and remaining balance. Early payments are mostly interest, while later payments are mostly principal.
      </p>

      <h3>How does amortization work?</h3>
      <p>
        Amortization spreads a loan into equal monthly payments. Each payment covers that month's interest charge plus a portion of the principal. As the balance decreases over time, less of each payment goes to interest and more goes to principal, even though the total payment stays the same.
      </p>

      <h3>Why do I pay more interest at the beginning of a loan?</h3>
      <p>
        Interest is calculated on the outstanding balance. At the start of a loan the balance is highest, so the interest charge is largest. As you pay down the principal over time, the interest portion shrinks and the principal portion grows within each fixed payment.
      </p>

      <h3>How can I pay off my loan faster?</h3>
      <p>
        You can pay off a loan faster by making extra principal payments, switching to biweekly payments (which adds one extra payment per year), rounding up your monthly payment, or refinancing to a shorter term. Even small additional payments can save thousands in interest.
      </p>

      <h3>What is the difference between amortization and simple interest?</h3>
      <p>
        Amortization means equal periodic payments that include both interest and principal, gradually paying off the loan to zero. Simple interest loans charge interest only on the current outstanding balance without a structured payoff schedule, which can result in a balloon payment.
      </p>


